By Tamary Chikiwa WOMEN in Bulawayo are failing to access contraceptives due to the current travel restrictions brought about by the Covid-19 pandemic.
Since January 5, the government has imposed a tough lockdown with only those working in essential services permitted free movement. A dusk-to-dawn curfew is also in place with ordinary citizens not allowed to be outside between 6pm and 6am. All these travel restrictions are now impacting heavily on the ability of women accessing family planning services. This was revealed during a Virtual Doctor Online Chat group hosted by the Women’s Institute for Leadership (WILD). The chat group engaged women and a practicing doctor Melisa Bhebe in discussing access to sexual and reproductive rights and other basic healthcare during the lockdown. “Contraceptives are only available in the central business district, but some of us are not essential service providers so we cannot just get in town without exemption letters,” revealed a woman by the name Jesca Ndlovu. Another woman, Novuyo Nkala said lack of access to contraceptives was leading to unplanned pregnancies, which is stretching already cash-strapped families. “This is a crisis because you end up getting pregnant and with this situation it really strains us,” she said. Bhebe advised women to stock contraceptives for two to three months in advance in order to avoid the current situation. “We urge you to be proactive during this crisis by preparing for the future through stocking up on contraceptives for two to three months in advance,” she said. Another issue highlighted by the discussion was the menstrual cycle challenges many women are facing. Bhebe offered simple home remedies like using warm water bottles on the lower abdomen and lower back to ease pain. She said the best over the counter medication for period pains that does not require a prescription from a doctor include Mefanamic acid tablets, Ibuprofen and Mepiridol. Bhebe advised those with heavy menstrual flows to enrich their diet with foods that can increase their blood levels such as spinach and other green leafy vegetables while liver, and other forms of red meat can also help. However, in cases where women feel dizzy or experience a continuous headache and difficulties breathing, she advised them to visit the clinic. Sponsored Links

    
      
        
          
